"No," she said, moved by a curious feeling of ingratitude;
                        "but I ought to be going. They'll be wondering where I
                        am."

"II" ventured the mother, stammering in her perturbation;
                        "shethey have been talking about her," she at last forced
                        herself to say.

"Sebastian Gerhardt?" he said, looking over his blotter;
                        "yes, here he is. Stealing coal and resisting an officer. Is he
                        your boy?"

"Go to bed, Jennie," said her mother solicitously;
                        "get the others to go. There's no use their sitting up. I
                        may think of something. You go to bed."

"Don't cry," he continued soothingly;
                        "everything will be all right. I told you that. You
                        needn't worry about anything."

Jennie had turned her head away and was staring at the floor. She faced him
                        now steadily. "He mustn't lose it," she said;
                        "it isn't fair that he should."

"Anyhow, this won't be the last of it, if I can help
                        it," he concluded. He was thinking that the storm might blow over;
                        once he had the money, and thenbut he hated compromises and subterfuges.

He took her hands, then her arms. Finally he drew her to him, and put his
                        arms about her waist. "Poor Letty!" he said;
                        "I'm not worth it. You'll be sorry."
